Polish Stocks: Getin, KGHM, Lotos, Orlen, PKO Bank, Pekao Move

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i   a n d   M o n i k a   R o z l a l
-- 
2011-09-09T16:08:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-09/polish-stocks-getin-kghm-lotos-orlen-pko-bank-pekao-move.html
Poland ’s WIG20 Index slumped 117.20,
or 5 percent, to close at 2,248.74 at 5:30 p.m. in Warsaw, the
steepest drop in three weeks.  The following are among the most active stocks on the
 Warsaw Stock Exchange  today. Stock symbols follow company names.  PKO Bank Polski SA (PKO PW), Poland’s biggest bank, slid
2.39 zloty, or 7.2 percent, to 30.9 zloty and  Bank Pekao SA (PEO)  , majority-owned by  UniCredit SpA (UCG) , declined 8.5 zloty, or 6.1
percent, to 130 zloty.  Getin Holding SA (GTN)  , the financial-
services group controlled by billionaire Leszek Czarnecki, sank
0.56 zloty, or 6.7 percent, to 7.85 zloty.  The zloty fell to the lowest level since July 2009 against
the euro, weakening as much as 2.2 percent, and dropped 1.9
percent to the Swiss franc, reviving concern borrower with
foreign-currency denominated loans will default. Foreign-
currency mortgage loans, most denominated in francs, totaled
188.2 billion zloty ($61 billion) in July, accounting for 63
percent of all home loans, according to the financial regulator.  KGHM Polska Miedz SA (KGH)  , the copper producer with the
biggest European mine output, fell for the first time in four
days, sliding 6.2 zloty, or 3.6 percent, to 167.6 zloty. Copper
tumbled the most in a month as President Barack Obama and
Federal Reserve Chairman  Ben S. Bernanke  failed to boost
investor confidence in the economy.  PKN Orlen SA (PKN PW), Poland’s biggest oil company, sank
1.56 zloty, or 4.1 percent, to 36.4 zloty.  Grupa Lotos SA (LTS)  , the second-largest refiner, lost 0.88 zloty, or 3.2
percent, to 26.92 zloty as crude oil tumbled as much as 3.7
percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
